55. For $n=1$ the theorem is true, since the sum of the digits of the number $\overline{a a a}$ is divisible by 3. Let the theorem be true for some value of $n$; we will show that it is true for $n+1$:

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \underbrace{\overline{a a a \ldots a}}_{3^{n+1} \text { digits }}=\overline{a a \ldots a} \underbrace{a a \ldots a}_{3^{n} \text { digits }} \underbrace{a a \ldots a}_{3^{n} \text { digits }} \underbrace{a a \ldots}_{3^{n} \text { digits }}=10^{2 \cdot 3^{n}} \underbrace{\overline{a a \ldots a}}_{3^{n} \text { digits }}+ \\
& +10^{3^{n}} \underbrace{\overline{a a \ldots a}}_{3^{n} \text { digits }}+\underbrace{\overline{a a \ldots a}}_{3^{n} \text { digits }}=\left(10^{2 \cdot 3^{n}}+10^{3^{n}}+1\right) \underbrace{a a a \ldots a}_{3^{n} \text { digits }} ;
\end{aligned}
$$

the number $10^{2 \cdot 3^{n}}+10^{3^{n}}+1$ is divisible by 3, since the sum of its digits is divisible by 3, therefore $\sqrt[3^{n+1} \text { digits }]{\overline{a a a \ldots a}}$ is divisible by $3 \cdot 3^{n}$, i.e., by $3^{n+1}$, thus the theorem is proved for any $n$.

