& \frac{a^{-1}-b^{-1}}{a^{-3}+b^{-3}}: \frac{a^{2} b^{2}}{(a+b)^{2}-3 a b} \cdot\left(\frac{a^{2}-b^{2}}{a b}\right)^{-1}=\frac{\frac{1}{a}-\frac{1}{b}}{\frac{1}{a^{3}}+\frac{1}{b^{3}}}: \frac{a^{2} b^{2}}{a^{2}+2 a b+b^{2}-3 a b} \times \\
& \times \frac{a b}{a^{2}-b^{2}}=\frac{\frac{b-a}{a b}}{\frac{a^{3}+b^{3}}{a^{3} b^{3}}} \cdot \frac{a^{2}-a b+b^{2}}{a^{2} b^{2}} \cdot \frac{a b}{a^{2}-b^{2}}=-\frac{(a-b) a^{3} b^{3}}{a b(a+b)\left(a^{2}-a b+b^{2}\right)^{2}} \times \\
& \times \frac{a^{2}-a b+b^{2}}{a^{2} b^{2}} \cdot \frac{a b}{(a+b)(a-b)}=-\frac{a b}{(a+b)^{2}}=-\frac{(1-\sqrt{2})(1+\sqrt{2})}{(1-\sqrt{2}+1+\sqrt{2})^{2}}=\frac{1}{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

Answer: $\frac{1}{4}$.

Let $n$ be an integer, if there exist $p_{1} \neq p_{2}$ two distinct prime numbers that divide $n$, then $n$ is not a power of a prime number. This is a consequence of the uniqueness of the prime factorization, but it can also be shown by applying Gauss's lemma: if $n=p^{k}$ and $p_{1}$ divides $n$ then $p_{1}$ divides $p$ because $p_{1}$ is prime. Similarly, $p_{2}$ divides $p$ so $p_{1}=p_{2}$.

There are infinitely many prime numbers. In particular, let $p_{1}, p_{2}, \cdots, p_{2 N-1}, p_{2 N}$ be the first $2 N$ prime numbers.

We seek an integer $M$ such that $p_{1} p_{2}$ divides $M$, $p_{3} p_{4}$ divides $M+1$, $\cdots$, $p_{2 N-1} p_{2 N}$ divides $M+N-1$. We are therefore looking for a solution to the system of congruences:

$$
\begin{gathered}
M \equiv 0\left[p_{1} p_{2}\right] \\
M \equiv 1\left[p_{3} p_{4}\right] \\
\cdots \\
M \equiv N-1\left[p_{2 N-1} p_{2 N}\right]
\end{gathered}
$$

The moduli of these equations are pairwise coprime. Thus, the Chinese Remainder Theorem shows that such an integer $M$ exists. By the previous remark, none of the integers $M, M+1, \cdots, M+N-1$ is a power of a prime number.

